<subSubSection id="45EBCE98FFDCBD65FF7BFAA8FBCA3CE9" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="0D4E9D13FFDCBD65FF7BFAA8FBE93C85" blockId="7.[136,1452,1348,1519]" box="[189,1136,1384,1411]" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">
<emphasis id="3F854101FFDCBD65FF7BFAA8FEFD3C85" bold="true" box="[189,356,1384,1410]" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">Etymology:—</emphasis>
The specific epithet is derived from the city name of the 
<typeStatus id="D24A23B1FFDCBD65FC19FAA9FB963C84" box="[991,1039,1385,1411]" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">type</typeStatus>
locality.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0D4E9D13FFDCBD65FF7BFA4CFAD13CA1" blockId="7.[136,1452,1348,1519]" box="[189,1352,1420,1446]" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">
<emphasis id="3F854101FFDCBD65FF7BFA4CFD803CA1" bold="true" box="[189,537,1420,1446]" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">Geographical distribution:—</emphasis>
Currently, 
<taxonomicName id="CAF1E690FFDCBD65FD57FA4DFCD63CA1" authorityName="Zhe Zhang, S. W. Yao &amp; S. Jin Zeng. A" authorityYear="2021" box="[657,847,1420,1446]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Phyllagathis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chongzuoensis">
<emphasis id="3F854101FFDCBD65FD57FA4DFCD63CA1" box="[657,847,1420,1446]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">P. chongzuoensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is only found in Chongzuo, 
<collectingRegion id="CF3553F1FFDCBD65FB49FA4CFB6B3CA1" box="[1167,1266,1420,1446]" country="China" name="Guangxi" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">Guangxi</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="75E6DD83FFDCBD65FB38FA4CFADC3CA1" box="[1278,1349,1420,1446]" name="China" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">China</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0D4E9D13FFDCBD65FF7BFA70FBCA3CE9" blockId="7.[136,1452,1348,1519]" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">
<emphasis id="3F854101FFDCBD65FF7BFA70FE573CCD" bold="true" box="[189,462,1456,1482]" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">Habitat and ecology:—</emphasis>
The new species grows in secondary broad-leaved evergreen sparse forests at an elevation of 
<quantity id="CA0930F6FFDCBD65FF60FA14FF743CE8" box="[166,237,1492,1519]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" unit="m" value="700.0">700 m</quantity>
as a lithophytic herb on cliffs composed of eroded sandstone on steep slopes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
